docs/combat_mixed_pattern_drift_ledger.md:13:- Preserve the canonical decisions already established in memory: typed hook/kernel seams stay canonical, presentation beats are non-authoritative, and shared combat systems should remain branch-light.
docs/combat_mixed_pattern_drift_ledger.md:21:| D3 | High | `src/main.rs`, `src/headless.rs`, `src/bin/combat_cli.rs`, `tests/validation_snapshot.rs`, `docs/m015_failure_ledger.md` | partially normalized local drift | S05 | App/headless kernel registration is normalized for S03-targeted proof; S05 still owns full CLI/runtime smoke and cwd-sensitive asset loading proof. |
docs/combat_mixed_pattern_drift_ledger.md:22:| D4 | High | `src/combat/blueprints/mod.rs`, `src/combat/blueprints/patamon.rs`, `tests/patamon_blueprint_seam.rs` | rewrite-scale follow-up candidate seeded in S03 | S04 / future blueprint slice | Expand the seeded blueprint seam deliberately; do not migrate all move ownership or add per-Digimon branches inside shared combat systems in this slice. |
docs/combat_mixed_pattern_drift_ledger.md:27:| D9 | Medium | `src/combat/observability.rs`, `src/headless.rs`, `src/bin/combat_cli.rs`, `tests/validation_snapshot.rs` | normalized for S03 snapshot path, downstream CLI proof remains | S05 | Keep validation snapshots backed by registered kernel resources; S05 should prove the same initialization path through real CLI/headless consumers. |
docs/combat_mixed_pattern_drift_ledger.md:37:The rewrite-scale work is the per-Digimon blueprint migration. S03 seeded D4 with a narrow Patamon module and a generic wrapper dispatch function, then left full move ownership and future per-Digimon expansion out of scope. This keeps shared combat systems branch-light while proving the flow `RON custom signals -> per-Digimon blueprint Rust module -> generic kernel hooks -> canonical state/events/snapshots`.
docs/combat_mixed_pattern_drift_ledger.md:54:**Handoff note:** R094 is about avoiding false authority claims. S04 should expand blueprint ownership only through typed custom signals and kernel transitions, not through shared-system character branches.
